2026-04-16 12:39:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module output stage / wiring between relay contacts and output cables'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU delivers a correct and stable ~12 V at its output. The control (ambient sensor) module clearly has this full 12 V available on its internal supply rails and relay input side, as confirmed by the last test. However, the measured voltage at the control‑module output / relay‑switched node is only about 0.36 V with respect to ground, and this low value is present continuously (it does not change during the lamp’s 20‑second brief flicker). The same ~0.36 V is seen at the load‑module input and at the anode of the protection diode, meaning the load module and diode are simply receiving the voltage passed to them by the control module.\n\nBecause\n- the relay coil and control electronics are correctly powered from the +12 V input,\n- the relay contacts were verified not to be opening or pulsing in step with the lamp dropout,\n- yet the node that is supposed to be the relay’s 12 V output sits at a fixed, low ~0.36 V,\n\nthis points to a fault local to the control module’s output path: either\n1) the relay common contact is not actually connected to the 12 V supply (e.g., an internal mis‑wire, open trace, or wrong terminal used), or\n2) the output cables are incorrectly soldered/terminated to the wrong relay contact or to a downstream point that is clamped around 0.36 V, or\n3) there is a high‑resistance/open connection between the relay’s intended 12 V output node and the external output terminal.\n\nAny of these defects would leave the control module electronics apparently normal while its external output never rises above a small leakage/clamped voltage, starving the load module. The brief 20‑second lamp ‘off’ symptom, given that the control‑module output and supply remain unchanged in the measurements, is then best explained as an artefact of an intermittently conducting path or the lamp operating at the edge of visibility on this low voltage. Correcting the internal wiring/connection between the relay contacts and the control‑module output terminals should restore a full 12 V output and eliminate the dropout behavior.'
