2026-04-16 12:40:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal supply / reference design (system assembled with wrong module variant expecting 0.36 V logic rail instead of 12 V output)', 'load module internal lamp wiring expecting 12 V at input but receiving only ~0.36 V from mismatched control module'] hypothesis_explanation='All measurements show the PSU is providing a correct 12 V and that the control‑module electronics themselves see 12 V on their internal supply. However, the relay‑switched output node that should pass the 12 V through to the load never rises above ~0.36 V relative to the common negative. This ~0.36 V level is present at the control module output cables, at the load‑module input, at the diode anode, and—after a further drop—across the lamps, which therefore see essentially 0 V and cannot be driven from this node. The value is constant in time and unaffected by the 20‑second flicker symptom, which means the lamps are not actually being switched by voltage but must be illuminated by some other effect (e.g., external light or misinterpretation of the symptom). All continuity and polarity tests show correct wiring between PSU, control module, and load module; prior repair attempts on the control output stage and ground wiring found no discrete faults. This points away from a single bad component and toward a systematic design or configuration mismatch: the ambient‑sensor module that has been installed is a variant whose ‘output’ node is in fact a low‑voltage logic/reference rail around 0.36 V, not a 12 V supply pass‑through as the load module requires. In other words, the wrong type/variant of ambient sensor module has been assembled into the system. The load module is correctly wired and expects 12 V at its input, but the control module can never provide more than its internal ~0.36 V level, so the load never receives operating voltage. Replacing the ambient sensor module with the correct 12 V‑switching version (or reconfiguring its internal reference so that the relay actually switches the 12 V rail through to the output pair) will restore proper lamp operation, and the apparent 20‑second flicker will disappear once the correct module is used.'
