2026-04-16 12:40:56 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['multimeter / measurement procedure used in prior diagnostics'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements on the control‑module output, load‑module input, and across both lamps show only about 0.36 V or essentially 0 V, and these values remain steady with no change when the lamp supposedly turns off every ~20 s. Yet the physical symptom is that the lamp is clearly operating from a healthy ~12 V source (PSU output verified at ~12 V and lamp visibly bright). If the circuit really had only 0.36 V across the load, the lamp could not be lit at all, let alone stably with only brief outages. Repeated tests have also confirmed correct polarity, correct inter‑module cabling, and an intact power‑supply and control‑module internal supply, and previous hypotheses about wiring faults or wrong module variants have been disproven.\n\nThe only remaining consistent explanation is that the diagnostic voltage readings themselves are invalid—most likely due to an error with the multimeter or with how its reference leads were connected during the tests (for example, a meter left on a low‑range or diode/continuity function, a nearly depleted meter battery causing erroneous readings, or the probes consistently placed on the same potential instead of across the true supply). This would yield small residual readings such as ~0.36 V regardless of the actual circuit voltage, and would also explain why no measured value ever changes during the observed flicker, even though the lamp behaviour suggests some intermittent event.\n\nTherefore the fault is not in the lamp, modules, or their wiring but in the measurement instrument or procedure that produced the 0.36 V data. Replacing/repairing or recalibrating the multimeter (and re‑measuring correctly across the actual lamp terminals and module outputs) will resolve the apparent diagnostic inconsistency and show the proper ~12 V behaviour of the circuit, allowing any real flicker cause—if it persists—to be investigated with valid measurements.'
