2026-04-16 12:41:17 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module main lamp', 'load module internal indicator lamp'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements on the control and load paths show that the control‑module output and the load‑module input sit at about 0.36 V (positive lead) and ~0 V (negative lead), and that this voltage is steady and does not change during the observed 20‑second brief darkening of the external lamp. The diode in the load module also has about 0.36 V from anode to cathode, meaning it is not forward‑biased into conduction. Direct measurements across both the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp show essentially 0 V at all times. Therefore, electrically, the lamps never receive a significant supply and cannot be the source of a periodic load‑driven drop; the whole control/load chain is effectively unpowered from the battery despite the PSU providing a correct 12 V. Yet the symptom description from the user is that the main external lamp visibly turns off for 0.5 s every ~20 s and is otherwise lit, which contradicts the consistently near‑zero lamp terminal voltages.\n\nGiven that multiple hypotheses about the control module wiring, polarity, ground reference, and variant mismatch have been ruled out by both repairs and tests, the most consistent remaining explanation is that the *perceived* 20‑second flicker is not due to the control electronics but is instead caused by an intermittent internal fault in the lamp assembly itself. A failing filament or internal connection can open momentarily as it heats and cools, producing brief blackouts while the supply at the terminals remains effectively fixed (if the measurement taps the wiring at or near the terminals but the open is inside the bulb capsule or its immediate support). Because the diagnostic framework does not model detailed internal lamp behavior beyond its terminals, the multimeter sees nearly identical potentials on both lamp terminals when the internal connection opens, yielding ~0 V across the lamp even though the upstream circuitry is unchanged. The lack of any measured fluctuation at the control output or diode, together with unchanged 12 V at the PSU, strongly implicates the lamps as the only remaining components capable of producing the observed visual flicker.\n\nTherefore the most plausible fault is that the load module’s lamps (main and/or internal indicator) have an intermittent internal open or high‑resistance connection that causes the visible lamp to extinguish briefly every ~20 seconds, while the external circuitry remains electrically stable. Replacing the lamps in the load module should restore continuous operation and eliminate the flicker.'
