2026-04-16 12:41:47 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module indicator LED / series resistor wiring (green LED branch shorted or miswired across the output cables)'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage measurements show a healthy 12 V present at the PSU output inside the power‑supply module, but only about 0.36 V appears on the control module output and at the load module input, and that 0.36 V is steady (no dropouts) even while the main lamp is observed to blink off briefly every ~20 s. The lamp terminals themselves sit essentially at ground potential (~0.0003 V), i.e., the lamp is not actually being driven from the measured 0.36 V node. Yet the user still sees an external lamp that appears to turn off and on. The only component that is confirmed to be ON and able to emit visible light in sync with the system is the green power‑supply indicator LED.\n\nGiven that all inter‑module cabling, polarity, and control‑module operation have tested normal, and that replacements of the control output stage, ground wiring, and load‑module lamps had no effect, the remaining plausible fault is that the power‑supply indicator LED circuit has been miswired so that its LED (and possibly its series resistor) is effectively across, or in series with, the load path, rather than just across the battery inside the power module. A common mis‑assembly would be the LED branch shorting or partially shorting the PSU output terminals through an incorrect connection of the LED/resistor leads.\n\nIn such a configuration, the LED would be powered correctly from the 12 V battery (so it is lit), but its misconnection across the external output cables would clamp the external outputs to a small forward‑biased LED voltage (~0.3–0.4 V as measured). This explains why every measurement at the control output and load input shows only ~0.36 V despite a good battery. The periodic apparent "lamp" flicker every ~20 s is then very likely the observer actually seeing changes in brightness (or reflections) of this miswired indicator LED rather than the main lamp, while the main lamp itself is effectively unpowered (confirmed by ~0 V across its terminals and by the fact that replacing the lamp did not fix the issue).\n\nTherefore the root cause is a wiring fault in the power‑supply module indicator LED branch—specifically, the LED/series resistor is incorrectly connected so that it clamps or diverts the supply from the output cables, leaving only ~0.36 V available to downstream modules. Correcting the LED/resistor wiring to be strictly in parallel with the battery, as per design, will restore a full 12 V to the output cables and allow the control and load modules to operate normally.'
