2026-04-16 12:42:05 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module battery / internal source'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage measurements at the control‑module output and at the load module (including directly across both lamps) are essentially 0 V with only ~0.36 V present on the supposed ‘+12 V’ rail after the relay. Yet the power‑supply indicator LED is lit and the PSU output, when measured at its own terminals, reads ~12 V. The lamp, however, is reported to be visibly on and blinking every 20 s.\n\nGiven that:\n- The cabling order and polarity between modules have been verified correct.\n- The control module internal supply is confirmed at ~12 V on its input side, and its relay contacts remain closed (no dropouts observed).\n- The wiring from relay contacts to output cables has been verified not faulty.\n- Both load lamps themselves are not faulty.\n- Between PSU negative, control negative, and load negative there are no offsets (all at ~0 V), eliminating ground‑reference errors.\n- The control‑module output node never rises above ~0.36 V, so there is no real 12 V delivered to the load path.\n\nThe only consistent explanation is that the ‘12 V’ indicated at the PSU output during earlier tests is not actually being sustained under system load or over time. The PSU’s internal source (the 12 V lithium battery or its immediate connections) must intermittently collapse towards a very low voltage (~0.36 V) under load while still allowing a tiny current sufficient to dimly light the small indicator LED and create the appearance of normal operation. Because state changes from non‑replacement diagnostics are not persistent, our tests that briefly measured 11.99 V could have captured an unloaded or transient condition, while the real persistent state during system operation is that the PSU source is essentially exhausted or has a very high internal resistance.\n\nThus, the root cause is a faulty internal energy source in the power supply module (the 12 V battery or its immediate internal source circuitry). Replacing/repairing the power‑supply module battery/source should restore a solid 12 V across the entire chain and eliminate the 20‑second blinking/dropout behavior.'
