2026-04-16 12:42:59 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module light‑sensor input circuit (photo‑device and its wiring)', 'ambient sensor module timing / sensitivity potentiometers and associated RC timing network'] hypothesis_explanation='All electrical measurements show that the relay contacts never open, the control‑module output node sits steadily at about 0.36 V above the common negative, and the load module lamps see essentially 0 V across them. At the same time, the visible symptom is a lamp that appears to turn off briefly every ~20 s, yet measured current from the PSU is a constant ~1.7 mA with no corresponding 20‑s modulation. This means the power path to the lamp is not being interrupted electrically; instead, the apparent flicker must be due to modulation of the lamp’s *driving of the visual scene* rather than its supply. In this design the only element that periodically reacts to ambient light with a time constant (seconds) is the ambient sensor front‑end: light sensor plus its RC timing network set by the timing and sensitivity potentiometers.\n\nThe prior tests confirmed:\n- PSU output is a clean ~12 V.\n- Control module electronics are referenced correctly to PSU negative and are powered from the 12 V input, not from the 0.36 V node.\n- Relay coil drive is steady (coil remains energized) and the contacts do not open during the dropout.\n- No mis‑wiring or polarity inversion exists between modules or cables.\n- The control output remains at ~0.36 V and is not near PSU positive, so the load is never actually presented with 12 V.\n- Lamps themselves are good, and their internal wiring and protection diode are OK.\n- Potentiometer sweeps produced no change in the 20‑second off‑blink behaviour, indicating that the timing/sensitivity network is not responding correctly to adjustment.\n\nThe only remaining plausible root cause consistent with: (1) correct wiring and module types, (2) a correctly energized relay that never releases, (3) a constant tiny current draw from the PSU, (4) a visually observed 20‑s optical blink with *no corresponding electrical change* in the power path, and (5) ineffective potentiometer adjustment, is a fault in the ambient sensor’s *input/timing circuit itself*. A defective or mis‑connected light sensor or RC network can drive the comparator/logic into a marginal oscillation or metastable state that periodically changes the *emitted* or perceived light without actually toggling the relay contacts or the 12 V power path in a way visible to our measurements.\n\nThus the most specific remaining hypothesis is that the ambient sensor module’s light‑sensor input stage (photo‑device, its bias network, and the timing/sensitivity potentiometer connections) is faulty. Repairing or replacing that sub‑circuit would remove the spurious 20‑second optical modulation and restore stable lamp operation, even though the main power path and relay contacts are electrically fine.'
