2026-04-16 12:43:38 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal wiring of relay contact to Control Input Cable (−) / sensor‑bias network'] hypothesis_explanation='Continuity testing with power off showed that the relay’s switched contact (which should form a clean series path from Control Input Cable (+) to Control Output Cable (+) only) is also resistively connected to Control Input Cable (−) at about 1.3 Ω and to the sensor‑bias resistor network. This means that when the relay is closed, the supposed +12 V through‑path is in fact being shunted through a low‑ohmic path toward the negative/input‑bias network, creating a heavy voltage divider or partial short instead of a proper high‑side switch. Under power, this manifests as only ~0.36 V appearing at the control output and load input, even though the PSU is at ~12 V and the relay coil is steadily energized at 12 V. The lamp therefore never sees anywhere near 12 V across it, which is consistent with the ~0 V measured directly across the lamp and the very low current (~1.7 mA) drawn from the PSU.\n\nThe 1.3 Ω connection from the relay contact to the Control Input Cable (−) is not expected in the intended design and cannot be explained by the high‑value ambient‑sensor components alone. It strongly suggests an internal wiring fault or solder bridge in the ambient sensor module that ties the relay contact (and thus Control Output Cable (+)) into the low‑side/sensor‑bias node. This defect would keep the output clamped near 0.36 V regardless of the potentiometer settings or light level, and it is consistent with all prior measurements, while the modules’ external cabling and the lamps themselves have been verified as correct.\n\nI therefore conclude that the root cause is a fault inside the ambient sensor module: the relay’s switched contact has been miswired or shorted into the low‑side/sensor‑bias network (near Control Input Cable (−)), preventing the module from delivering the full 12 V to the load. Repair should focus on correcting this internal connection so that the relay contact isolates completely from the negative/bias network and connects only between Control Input Cable (+) and Control Output Cable (+).'
