description: With all modules connected and the lamp exhibiting the 20‑second flicker, measure (1) the DC voltage between the control module internal supply rail that feeds the light‑sensor/relay driver and its internal ground, and (2) the voltage across the relay’s switched contacts. Confirm whether the relay contacts ever open or the module’s internal supply ever dips during the lamp dropout, and verify that the control module electronics are actually powered from the +12 V input rather than from the low‑voltage output node., outcome='The control module internal supply appears to be at approximately 12 V (Control Input Cable (+): ~11.99 V; Control Input Cable (−): ~0 V), indicating the electronics are powered from the +12 V input side. The relay’s switched node is at ~0.36 V (Control Relay / Control Output Cable (+)), and the relay contacts did not open or cause a supply dip during the observed lamp dropout.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=125.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> load module internal lamp and indicator,
description: Visually inspect the load module by opening its panel or peephole in a darkened room and watch both the main external lamp and the small internal indicator lamp continuously for at least one full 20‑second cycle. Confirm whether the main lamp actually turns fully off, only dims, or remains steady while perhaps only the internal indicator flickers, and verify that both lamps are indeed powered by this circuit and not by any hidden or external source., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> load module lamp circuit (main and indicator),
description: Measure the DC voltage directly across the main lamp terminals and then across the small internal indicator lamp terminals in the load module, while the 20‑second brief turn‑off is occurring. Log these voltages versus time through at least one full cycle to see whether the lamp supply actually drops or if the lamps flicker despite a steady supply., outcome='The measured voltage across both the main load lamp and the internal indicator lamp remains at approximately 0.0003 V on both terminals throughout the measurement. No evidence of a supply drop or flicker under load was observed in these readings.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor module indicator LED / reference node,
description: Measure the DC voltage of the ambient‑sensor module’s ‘switched‑cables indicator’ LED: (a) between its anode and the control‑module negative, and (b) between its cathode and the control‑module negative, while the system operates. Compare these with the previously observed ~0.36 V output node to verify how the indicator is referenced and whether the 0.36 V level is in fact the module’s internal ground rather than a true low‑side output, helping to identify a possible systematic 0.36 V level shift or measurement reference issue., outcome='The requested action could not be mapped to any recognized diagnostic operation. Only actions from the available action list are supported (e.g. measure_voltage, test_continuity, inspect_connections, verify_repair, …).\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=0.0, cost_breakdown=[], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> measurement reference between modules,
description: With the system powered, use a multimeter to measure DC voltage between (1) PSU negative and control‑module negative, (2) PSU negative and load‑module negative input, and (3) control‑module negative output and load‑module negative input. This checks for any unexpected voltage offsets or mis‑referenced grounds between modules that could explain the persistent ~0.36 V readings at the control output and load input despite a healthy 12 V supply., outcome='Measured voltages at the PSU Output Cable (−) are ~0.0 V / 0.0002 V, indicating it is essentially at ground potential. The Control Output Cable (−) measures ~0.0003 V on both terminals, also essentially at ground potential. No polarity inversion is indicated by these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Observe -> inter‑module cable connections and module stacking order,
description: Inspect how the three modules are physically connected: verify that the power‑supply output cables are actually mated to the ambient‑sensor module input pair, and that the ambient‑sensor output pair is mated to the load module input pair. Also confirm that no cable pair is looped back into the same module or cross‑connected between wrong faces (e.g., PSU directly to load while control module is only tapped by a single lead). Note any non‑standard or asymmetric cabling or stacking that could leave the lamp powered from the PSU while measurements are being taken on an unpowered control/load path., outcome='The PSU Output Cables (+/−) are correctly connected to the Control Input Cables (+/−), and the Control Output Cables (+/−) are correctly connected to the Load Input Cables (+/−). No cable pair is looped back into the same module, and there are no cross‑connections such as PSU directly to load or single‑lead taps. No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED in any of the inspected cable connections.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=100.0, cost_breakdown=[('invert_enclosure', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0), ('inspect_connections', 10.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor module output cables vs PSU positive,
description: Measure the DC voltage between the Control Output Cable (+) and the PSU Output Cable (+), and between the Control Output Cable (−) and the PSU Output Cable (+), while the lamp is operating. This will determine whether the control‑module output node that measures ~0.36 V above its own negative is actually near the PSU positive (i.e., the meter references have been swapped so that the lamp really has ~12 V across it), revealing a systematic reference error versus a true low output level., outcome='The Control Output Cable (+) is at approximately 0.36 V relative to ground, and the Control Output Cable (−) is near 0 V, so the control output node is not near the PSU Output Cable (+), which is at about 11.99 V. No polarity inversion between labeled (+) and (−) cables is indicated by these measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=60.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor module light sensor / relay driver circuit,
description: Measure the DC voltage at the relay‑coil drive node (the transistor or driver output that energizes the sensor‑operated relay) with respect to the control‑module negative, while the system runs through at least one 20‑second cycle. Log whether this drive signal ever changes state or glitches in sync with the brief lamp dropout, confirming whether the ambient‑sensor control logic is periodically toggling or if the relay remains fully and steadily energized., outcome='The control relay drive node measures about 12.0 V on its positive side and 0.36 V on its negative side, indicating a steady energized state during the test. The Control Input Cable (−) measures essentially 0 V on both conductors, with no logged state change or glitch correlated to the lamp dropout.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=45.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> power supply module to ambient sensor module cabling (under load current),
description: Measure the DC current flowing in series with the PSU Output Cable (+) feeding the ambient sensor module while the lamp is operating and exhibiting the 20‑second dropouts. Insert an ammeter in series with the PSU positive lead to the control module and log the current over at least one full 20‑second cycle. This will reveal whether the load current actually drops or pulses when the visible lamp ‘blinks’, distinguishing a true power interruption from a purely optical effect or an unmonitored parallel path., outcome='Measured DC current through PSU Output Cable (+) is 0.001666 A while the lamp is exhibiting the 20-second dropouts. No polarity inversion is indicated in this measurement.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=20.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_current', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None), DiagnosticActionResult(action=
name: Test -> ambient sensor module relay switched path continuity,
description: With power OFF, disconnect the control module from both PSU and load. Using a multimeter in continuity/ohms mode, identify the relay’s two switched contact terminals inside the control module, then check continuity from each contact to its corresponding external output cable terminal. Verify that one relay contact is solidly connected to the Control Input Cable (+) and the other to the Control Output Cable (+), and that neither is inadvertently tied to the control‑module negative or to any 0.36 V internal node., outcome='The relay’s switched contact is solidly connected to both the Control Output Cable (+) (0.01 Ω) and the Control Input Cable (+) (0.10 Ω). There is a resistive path from the relay contact to the Control Input Cable (−) (1.30 Ω) and to internal components (Sensor Bias Resistor at 0 Ω, Ambient Light Sensor at ~5 kΩ). No polarity inversion between (+) and (−) cables is indicated by these continuity measurements.\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.', precise_action_cost=175.0, cost_breakdown=[('open_inspection_panel', 5.0), ('test_continuity', 20.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0), ('test_path_continuity', 30.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
